1
00:00:19,740 --> 00:00:21,103
Evening and greetings.

2
00:00:21,242 --> 00:00:22,905
I trust you had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:22,925 --> 00:00:26,528
I do not say happy, though I wish it has been happy.

4
00:00:27,611 --> 00:00:43,790
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa

5
00:00:44,445 --> 00:00:57,284
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

6
00:00:58,968 --> 00:01:01,030
It looks like my clock's gone wrong.

7
00:01:04,956 --> 00:01:05,498
Ten minutes.

8
00:01:05,697 --> 00:01:13,069
OK, so I've had two rather sad e-mails.

9
00:01:13,959 --> 00:01:18,186
We've discussed all this business about death.

10
00:01:19,147 --> 00:01:24,635
And then, of course, there's the complementary side, which, of course, is grief.

11
00:01:26,817 --> 00:01:39,075
One writer says, these last years has brought to my door a series of griefs, the deaths of close ones and beloveds, some unexpected due to suicide, some through the combination of illness.

12
00:01:40,016 --> 00:01:43,460
One, the most beloved from a cardiac arrest.

13
00:01:43,609 --> 00:01:46,153
And she also lost her pet.

14
00:01:47,634 --> 00:01:54,861
And they themselves were diagnosed with cancer, but is in remission now, is in remission.

15
00:01:59,165 --> 00:02:06,274
And she's found that during this lockdown, a lot of this grief and sorrow arising, particularly in dreams during meditation.

16
00:02:06,894 --> 00:02:13,161
So when we're alone, these turbulences, whatever they are, they tend to come back to haunt us.

17
00:02:15,486 --> 00:02:32,103
And very recently, a very sad case, a very sad situation of a man, a young man, well, youngish, 34 from my point of view, youngish, Pete, who's had a seizure at night and died, leaving his wife and three small children.

18
00:02:32,302 --> 00:02:40,670
So that, of course, is a huge shock to somebody who has to suffer that, to all those close to him, you know.

19
00:02:42,992 --> 00:02:44,835
So this...

20
00:02:45,861 --> 00:02:54,652
This problem of grief, obviously, is coming up for all those people who've died, who've lost somebody to this coronavirus.

21
00:02:55,614 --> 00:03:01,140
And, you know, it's good just to say something a little bit about all that.

22
00:03:02,762 --> 00:03:08,889
First of all, is to try to make a distinction, just using these words, between sorrow and grief.

23
00:03:09,050 --> 00:03:10,131
I mean, they're interchangeable.

24
00:03:11,733 --> 00:03:13,134
Sorrow is that...

25
00:03:14,060 --> 00:03:42,328
Trembling as the Buddha would say in the heart what we would call empathy Where you feel the sorrow of somebody else And you can say that when somebody dies in an unfortunate way Or they're they're too young to die died before their time as we say That there's a certain sorrow on their behalf and

26
00:03:42,781 --> 00:03:46,104
as a thing that they could have offered more to society.

27
00:03:46,144 --> 00:03:47,544
They could have lived a longer life.

28
00:03:48,466 --> 00:03:51,688
But generally, there's a sense of sorrow about it.

29
00:03:52,129 --> 00:04:00,556
And that's really looking at it, as it were, from their point of view, not from our point of view.

30
00:04:03,419 --> 00:04:12,027
When we see, I mean, the big case, of course, was that little boy on the beach, which caused Angela Merkel to allow

31
00:04:12,784 --> 00:04:16,728
immigrants in, you know, well, refugees, excuse me.

32
00:04:17,831 --> 00:04:23,617
So there was a movement there, a sort of a resonance in the heart with the suffering of others.

33
00:04:24,177 --> 00:04:38,413
And that sorrow normally demands some sort of action into compassion or else it lies as unrequited, it lies as a sort of pain in the heart, you see.

34
00:04:38,874 --> 00:04:41,997
And of course, if you can't do anything, then

35
00:04:42,333 --> 00:04:45,177
you can at least send your good wishes.

36
00:04:45,197 --> 00:04:48,300
You can do the meditation on contemplation.

37
00:04:49,562 --> 00:04:51,225
And you have to accept that.

38
00:04:51,264 --> 00:04:52,065
You can't do anything.

39
00:04:52,086 --> 00:04:52,987
You can't do anything.

40
00:04:53,026 --> 00:04:56,391
There's no point in beating ourselves up about that.

41
00:04:57,173 --> 00:05:05,624
So in a sense, that sorrow is part and parcel of our communication, our being with people.

42
00:05:05,704 --> 00:05:09,910
I'd like to read this really lovely poem by

43
00:05:10,108 --> 00:05:12,711
John Donne, I won't read it all, just the main section.

44
00:05:13,853 --> 00:05:21,322
John Donne was a poet in the Restoration period, James I, all that sort of thing.

45
00:05:23,504 --> 00:05:27,810
And he says, No man is an island, entire of itself.

46
00:05:28,851 --> 00:05:32,136
Each is a piece of the continent, a part of the main.

47
00:05:33,538 --> 00:05:38,023
If a clod is washed away by the sea, Europe is the less.

48
00:05:39,269 --> 00:05:44,476
each man's death diminishes me, for I am involved in mankind.

49
00:05:45,759 --> 00:05:51,927
Therefore, send not to know for whom the bell tolls, it tolls for thee.

50
00:05:53,028 --> 00:05:56,595
So in other words, every man's death is also a little death within me.

51
00:05:59,218 --> 00:06:04,446
You know, I had a friend down in Cornwall I would visit on occasion, and he died.

52
00:06:04,485 --> 00:06:06,970
And of course, I've lost that relationship.

53
00:06:07,069 --> 00:06:08,432
So something in me has

54
00:06:08,699 --> 00:06:37,069
been lost and there's a sort of wholesomeness about that because we need we need people we need friendships we need to be able to relate to communicate it's just part of that feed hopefully next tomorrow I'll be talking about the nutriments and you'll see that this was recognized by the Buddha that you we do need other people and that's and that's obviously

55
00:06:37,267 --> 00:06:39,250
That's obvious when it comes to meditation.

56
00:06:39,310 --> 00:06:47,543
It's so much easier to suffer when you know everybody else in the room is going through something similar than just sitting on your own.

57
00:06:48,404 --> 00:06:57,759
And I'm especially aware of people who are actually in isolation because of medical problems and stuff like that.

58
00:06:58,319 --> 00:07:01,064
So it's difficult, difficult just to be on your own.

59
00:07:01,184 --> 00:07:06,752
These days, of course, it is attenuated, shall we say, by modern technology.

60
00:07:08,757 --> 00:07:20,170
Interestingly enough, when the Buddha's two main disciples died, that's Moggallana and Sariputta.

61
00:07:21,610 --> 00:07:23,432
I'm going to read this little bit, actually.

62
00:07:26,896 --> 00:07:27,538
Let's see now.

63
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:35,225
Yes, this again is taken from the book Mindfully Facing Disease and Death by Venerable Annalio.

64
00:07:35,846 --> 00:07:36,687
Highly recommend it.

65
00:07:36,937 --> 00:07:44,305
There is another book, by the way, which I might have mentioned, Living in the Light of Death, The Art of Being Truly Alive by Larry Rosenberg.

66
00:07:46,427 --> 00:07:58,076
Now, when Sariputta died, Ananda said, I declare having myself known them on attaining full awakening before establishments of mindfulness and so on and so forth.

67
00:07:58,117 --> 00:07:59,579
These have all been taken away.

68
00:07:59,639 --> 00:08:02,762
In other words, Ananda is grieving the loss of his teacher.

69
00:08:03,482 --> 00:08:06,365
And there's a series of questions that the Buddha asks him.

70
00:08:06,384 --> 00:08:06,625
Well,

71
00:08:06,992 --> 00:08:10,817
Has he taken away your ability to observe your mind?

72
00:08:11,199 --> 00:08:16,867
He goes through the discourse on how to establish right awareness.

73
00:08:17,286 --> 00:08:20,011
Has he taken away your ability to investigate?

74
00:08:20,432 --> 00:08:26,139
Has he taken away your ability to become fully liberated yourself?

75
00:08:26,199 --> 00:08:29,524
And of course, Ananda says no.

76
00:08:37,047 --> 00:08:54,427
And he says, and then the Buddha gives him his advice, which you also get right at the end of the discourse, which tells about the last few days of the Buddha.

77
00:08:54,988 --> 00:09:00,894
He said, he reminds him that he himself, the Buddha himself, the Tathagata would go, you see.

78
00:09:04,620 --> 00:09:08,505
Therefore, do not be so very sad, Ananda.

79
00:09:09,187 --> 00:09:12,971
You should know that soon that the targeter will also be of the past.

80
00:09:12,990 --> 00:09:18,378
Therefore, Ananda, you should have yourself as an island by relying on yourself.

81
00:09:18,798 --> 00:09:22,022
You should have the Dharma as an island by relying on the Dharma.

82
00:09:22,302 --> 00:09:26,788
You should not have another island, no other reliance.

83
00:09:26,807 --> 00:09:33,395
So now this seems contrary to what we've just read from John Donne, that every man isn't an island.

84
00:09:34,658 --> 00:09:38,023
But of course, we're talking about two different things.

85
00:09:38,563 --> 00:09:48,618
We talk about our relationship, our necessary relationship with other people, and the fact that the relationship goes wrong.

86
00:09:48,898 --> 00:09:50,399
Now, that's the problem.

87
00:09:51,120 --> 00:09:53,224
Where does the relationship go wrong?

88
00:09:53,485 --> 00:09:55,326
It goes wrong through attachment.

89
00:09:56,328 --> 00:09:56,990
We all know this.

90
00:09:57,289 --> 00:10:02,116
And attachment is just another way of saying a psychological dependency on somebody that

91
00:10:02,636 --> 00:10:07,623
for my happiness, for my security, for my comfort, and so on and so forth.

92
00:10:08,563 --> 00:10:17,413
And what the Buddha is saying is, you know, when you put that aside, you've got to find your own inner safety, your own inner place.

93
00:10:18,154 --> 00:10:21,258
And, of course, we're doing that every time we sit in meditation.

94
00:10:21,278 --> 00:10:25,062
We're discovering this, the observer, the feeler, the one who knows.

95
00:10:26,744 --> 00:10:31,750
And, you know, when that's very clear to you, when you are really

96
00:10:32,320 --> 00:10:49,135
the one who knows within yourself and everything else is happening, the body with its feeling and the heart with its emotions, the mind with its thought, when you're quite separate from that and you are the observer, the feeler, you know, ask yourself, what's it like?

97
00:10:49,256 --> 00:10:50,798
You know, is it okay?

98
00:10:50,817 --> 00:10:55,783
You know, is it worth being there most of the time?

99
00:10:56,102 --> 00:10:58,985
Not so much as the observer, but in that sort of coolness.

100
00:11:00,873 --> 00:11:14,605
The Buddha actually says that when Sariputta dies, and Moggallana too, Moggallana was murdered, it seems, by another sect who got, I don't know, was jealous of him or something.

101
00:11:16,006 --> 00:11:27,217
When these two main disciples died, and they would have been a similar age, because he was 35 when he began teaching, and they became very quickly his disciples, his first disciples.

102
00:11:27,467 --> 00:11:32,134
So they would have been, you know, late 20s, 30s, so very close to him in age.

103
00:11:32,634 --> 00:11:40,625
He said that the sangha, that's the order of monks and nuns, felt empty without them, see?

104
00:11:40,764 --> 00:11:41,927
So that's the other side.

105
00:11:42,027 --> 00:11:45,532
That's the business of no man is an island.

106
00:11:45,552 --> 00:11:53,402
But we've got this more negative side, which is really about the grief that we feel.

107
00:11:53,841 --> 00:11:57,407
So, you know, this...

108
00:11:57,639 --> 00:11:59,863
This grief has to be felt.

109
00:11:59,942 --> 00:12:00,923
It has to be suffered.

110
00:12:02,346 --> 00:12:05,429
It's what's left.

111
00:12:06,250 --> 00:12:13,279
It's what is the consequence, the karma, the karma of unwholesome relationship.

112
00:12:13,760 --> 00:12:15,163
Now, you have to be careful here.

113
00:12:15,182 --> 00:12:16,303
This isn't immoral.

114
00:12:16,604 --> 00:12:23,953
You know, it's not as though you go to hell forever because you had an attachment to somebody.

115
00:12:24,234 --> 00:12:24,794
Not at all.

116
00:12:25,044 --> 00:12:31,332
It's unwholesome in the sense that eventually it causes pain and it causes us to suffer.

117
00:12:32,033 --> 00:12:39,744
And grief, especially with sudden death, as we had with Pete who died a couple of nights back.

118
00:12:40,245 --> 00:12:43,207
I meant to bring this up last night, actually, but I wasn't here.

119
00:12:43,869 --> 00:12:53,061
And with this woman who's come with all these series of griefs, that really...

120
00:12:53,345 --> 00:13:00,615
it's extremely difficult to stay with that shock, with the constant death of people in our lives.

121
00:13:00,934 --> 00:13:05,902
And of course, as you grow older, as I am, you know, people begin to disappear.

122
00:13:05,922 --> 00:13:10,368
And eventually, if you live long enough, it's just you.

123
00:13:10,509 --> 00:13:13,572
I mean, you've made other friends, younger friends, whatever.

124
00:13:14,134 --> 00:13:20,062
But all those old friends that you've known for years, that maybe even go back to childhood, they've all gone, you see.

125
00:13:20,743 --> 00:13:23,166
And you're just left there with the

126
00:13:23,432 --> 00:13:24,514
with all these memories.

127
00:13:25,575 --> 00:13:40,587
So grief, grief is that, is that, you know, it's that sore, the wound, which is caused when something from the heart is taken out, is ripped out when it's a shock like that.

128
00:13:41,469 --> 00:13:53,119
And there's no other way but to sort of sit with it and, and to give the, give the heart time to heal and to know that this is the cause of a,

129
00:13:53,317 --> 00:14:00,384
of a psychological dependency, but that isn't to take away the fact that there was also love.

130
00:14:00,565 --> 00:14:04,369
There was also a sense of care for the person.

131
00:14:04,389 --> 00:14:06,650
So, you know, sometimes you get confused about that.

132
00:14:07,131 --> 00:14:17,761
And of course the big confusion is to think that as your grief diminishes, it's, um, it's telling you that you don't love the person as you used to, you're losing their love.

133
00:14:17,782 --> 00:14:20,304
Well, if you get into that, you're, you're into a, um,

134
00:14:20,690 --> 00:14:26,638
into a never ending cycle of grief, which lessens and then you have to grieve a bit more.

135
00:14:26,677 --> 00:14:32,666
You have to keep pumping it up because you're trying to prove that the grief you have is the measure of your love.

136
00:14:33,506 --> 00:14:49,548
But if the grief process is gone through in its normal passage, which they say is about nine months, and I'm sure you all know if you happen to have grief in your life, there is a charity cruise

137
00:14:50,102 --> 00:15:04,217
which helps people, that if you allow the heart to express its pain, then over a period of up to nine months, you know, it begins to dissipate.

138
00:15:04,618 --> 00:15:14,028
Not that it doesn't come back in little blips, but at least the terrible pain, especially the first three, six months, begins to dissipate.

139
00:15:14,668 --> 00:15:19,653
And slowly one begins to contact that loved one has.

140
00:15:20,225 --> 00:15:22,466
that love, that care that one had.

141
00:15:22,947 --> 00:15:26,631
And, of course, that brings up beautiful memories and joy arises.

142
00:15:26,912 --> 00:15:33,798
I mean, that would be the normal passage of things, yeah.

143
00:15:33,938 --> 00:15:40,666
So I think I've... Oh, yeah.

144
00:15:40,687 --> 00:15:46,873
This happened as a woman...

145
00:15:47,376 --> 00:15:51,282
a lay woman who was a great supporter of the Buddha.

146
00:15:51,302 --> 00:15:52,822
It goes right back to his early days.

147
00:15:54,424 --> 00:16:02,615
And she turns up one day at the monastery with her hair drenched, weeping, crying out in sorrow.

148
00:16:03,576 --> 00:16:09,383
And it says, she went to see the Buddha in the middle of the day in spite of the sun, you see.

149
00:16:10,264 --> 00:16:17,011
Her favorite grandchild, Datta, who had always helped to distribute arms, had suddenly passed away.

150
00:16:17,836 --> 00:16:26,288
And when she told the Blessed One of her sorrow, he asked whether she wanted to have as many children and grandchildren as there were people in the city of Sarvati.

151
00:16:26,447 --> 00:16:27,649
That's the capital of Kosala.

152
00:16:28,571 --> 00:16:29,793
And she joyfully agreed.

153
00:16:30,433 --> 00:16:34,558
But how many people die in Sarvati every day, said the Blessed One.

154
00:16:34,578 --> 00:16:40,967
And she considered and said, oh, Lord, in Sarvati, nine or ten people, five or three or two people.

155
00:16:41,089 --> 00:16:42,429
Excuse me just a minute.

156
00:16:42,450 --> 00:16:42,831
That's my alarm.

157
00:16:43,299 --> 00:16:47,664
Two people, or at least one, die every day.

158
00:16:47,784 --> 00:16:49,427
Sovereignty is never free of dying.

159
00:16:50,347 --> 00:16:57,716
And being asked whether in this case she would ever be without sorrow, she had to admit that she would feel sorrow every single day.

160
00:16:58,317 --> 00:17:03,883
So the Blessed One said, those who have a hundred loved ones have a hundred sorrows.

161
00:17:04,303 --> 00:17:08,126
Those who have ninety, all the way down to one, have only one sorrow.

162
00:17:08,448 --> 00:17:11,451
And those who have no loved ones have no sorrow.

163
00:17:12,325 --> 00:17:17,269
Those alone, I say, are without sorrow, without suffering, without desperation.

164
00:17:17,769 --> 00:17:22,914
And, of course, he's not talking about love and care.

165
00:17:22,954 --> 00:17:34,246
He's talking about what happens when you're attached, when you are dependent on somebody for some well-being, for some happiness, for some comfort.

166
00:17:34,786 --> 00:17:40,932
And that, of course, is something that we simply have to work through.

167
00:17:41,519 --> 00:17:46,545
And as I say, the not to make the mistake between grief and love.

168
00:17:46,885 --> 00:17:47,866
Grief is the measure.

169
00:17:48,728 --> 00:17:52,172
The way I'm using the word grief is the measure about attachment.

170
00:17:52,573 --> 00:17:53,874
And we just have to suffer it.

171
00:17:54,255 --> 00:18:00,942
And that's that's something to remind ourselves, too, that, you know, punishment is out of the question in Buddhism.

172
00:18:00,962 --> 00:18:05,107
You don't have to punish anybody or punish yourself or or get angry with yourself.

173
00:18:05,628 --> 00:18:10,615
It's not it's not it's not all we're doing that is adding more suffering to the suffering.

174
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:13,067
All we have to do is suffer consequences.

175
00:18:13,448 --> 00:18:15,032
That's all we're asked to do.

176
00:18:16,076 --> 00:18:19,749
And allow the heart, give it time to heal.

177
00:18:20,009 --> 00:18:20,171
Yeah.

178
00:18:21,736 --> 00:18:22,176
Very good.

179
00:18:22,458 --> 00:18:24,605
So I think I'm getting on there.

180
00:18:24,625 --> 00:18:25,709
2010, I think.

181
00:18:26,351 --> 00:18:28,417
My clock's unfortunately stopped.

